				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{SD}}_{\text{of change}}=\sqrt{[({{\mathrm{SD}}_{\mathrm{pre}-\mathrm{test}})}^{2}+({{\mathrm{SD}}_{\mathrm{post}-\mathrm{test}})}^{2}-\left(2r\times {\mathrm{SD}}_{\mathrm{pre}-\mathrm{test}}\times {\mathrm{SD}}_{\mathrm{post}-\mathrm{test}}\right)] }.$$\end{document}SDof change=[(SDpre-test)2+(SDpost-test)2-2r×SDpre-test×SDpost-test].

An r value of 0.9 was the pre-post correlation for all estimations, as previous studies have reported large pre- to post-test correlations (e.g., 0.85–0.99) on upper and lower body strength tests [5, 28–30]. The standardized ES and standard error (SE) of the standardized ES were computed as follows [31]:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
